  "title": "Conductors - charge on three metal plates",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three identical metal plates arranged parallel to each other, separated my small gaps. From bottom to top, they have charges negative lowercase q, 0, and positive lowercase q.\" src=\"/images/b3266cb93f7c2e924157d5bf91708f04.svg\"></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Three identical metal plates are arranged with parallel surfaces separated by relatively small distances, as shown in the figure. The top plate has a net charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive lowercase q\"><math alttext=\"positive lowercase q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mstyle></math></span></span>, the middle plate is uncharged, and the bottom plate has net charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative lowercase q\"><math alttext=\"negative lowercase q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>âˆ’</mo><mi>q</mi></math></span></span>. The top plate is brought close to the middle plate, so they touch and stay on contact. How do the charge distributions on the top and middle plates change after they touch?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i4",
    "choices": [
      {
        "label": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive lowercase q\"><math alttext=\"positive lowercase q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mstyle></math></span></span> charge is distributed evenly throughout the top and middle plates.</p>",
        "value": "i1"
      },
      {
